Resting State Functional Connectivity and Depression: Sex Differences in the DMN and ECN

Abstract

Major depressive disorder (MDD) is characterized by altered connectivity in the default mode network (DMN) and executive control network (ECN). This research explores sex differences in resting-state connectivity between the DMN and ECN in 66 participants (21 controls and 45 depression patients). Time series data were extracted from six regions of interest, and functional connectivity was assessed using Pearsons correlation. T-tests and False Discovery Rate (FDR) corrections were applied, along with calculating effect sizes. Before applying the FDR correction, significant differences in DMN-ECN connectivity were found between controls and depressed patients, with medium to large effect sizes. Males in the control group showed stronger connectivity in cognitive control regions compared to females, while females with depression exhibited stronger connectivity between the DMN and ACC. However, none of the results remained significant after FDR correction. These findings suggest potential sex-based differences in connectivity patterns, though larger samples are needed to confirm these results.

Introduction

Major depressive disorder (MDD) is characterized by disruptions in brain networks, especially the default mode network (DMN), executive control network (ECN), and salience network (SN) (Bezmaternykh et al., 2021). It has been found that within-DMN connectivity increases in depressed individuals, while connectivity between the DMN and ECN may decrease, which explains the cognitive and emotional symptoms usually seen in depression (Bezmaternykh et al., 2021). Increased connectivity in the DMN in depressed patients include the following brain regions: precuneus, posterior cingulate cortex (PCC), bilateral temporoparietal junction (TPJ), and the medial prefrontal cortex (mPFC). The increased connectivity within this network is related to rumination, self-referential thinking, and difficulties in disengaging from internal though processes (Bezmaternykh et al., 2021). The decreased connectivity between the DMN and ECN involves the following brain regions: mPFC (part of the DMN), dorsolateral prefrontal cortex (dlPFC; part of the ECN), and the anterior cingulate cortex (ACC; linked to ECN). The decreased connectivity between these regions is related to cognitive deficits, problems with executive function and emotional regulation (Bezmaternykh et al., 2021).
Depression affects women and men differently. For example, women are more likely to present with depression (Eid et al., 2019). Men and women suffering from depression also differ in monoaminergic system markers, immune system markers, and neuroplasticity, as well as in some hormones and neurotransmitters (Labaka et al., 2018), and potentially distinct neural mechanisms underlying symptoms (Bangasser et al., 2021). Given the research on sex differences in depression, there remains a gap in literature regarding rest-state connectivity patterns in depressed patients. Understanding these differences allow for a broader understanding of depression and implications for personalized treatment.
Given the importance of the DMN and ECN in depression, as well as sex differences in symptomology based on previous research, I aim to investigate whether there is a difference between males and females in resting state functional connectivity in patients with depression compared to a healthy control group. The dataset I used to test my research question is the dataset from Bezmaternykh and colleagues article (2021). It included 21 control subjects and 51 subjects with depression and was downloaded from OpenNeuro (2021).

Method

Participants

Participant data was obtained from the participants.tsv file. The dataset included 72 participants. Participants 1-51 were MDD patients, while participants 52-72 were controls. Because I wanted to replicate the researchers analysis, I split the participants into controls (N=21) and depression patients (N=45) first. Six depression patients were lost due to a lack of a BOLD file. Then, to test my own research question, I divided the participants to four groups: control males (N=6), control females (N=15), depressed males (N=13), and depressed females (N=32).

Data Preprocessing

The functional images were acquired with a repetition time (TR) of 2.5 seconds. Preprocessing of the data was done using fMRIPrep (by the researchers): this included motion correction, slice trimming, spatial normalization to MNI152 space, and smoothing with a 6mm full-width half maximum Gaussian Kernel. Despite the data being preprocessed, I found that I should regress the confounds anyway again, so I regressed out motion parameters, white matter, cerebrospinal fluid (CSF), and global signal. Figure 1 compares the signal with and without confound regression. The required libraries for the analysis are loaded below.

Atlas and Regions of Interest (ROIs)

In their original article, the researchers utilized independent component analysis (ICA) to identify resting-state networks in the brain. They decomposed the fMRI data into components that represent different functional networks. They utilized a group-based ICA approach, calculating temporal correlations between the components to assess connectivity differences. In my own analysis, I utilized the Harvard-Oxford cortical atlas to extract the time series from six ROIs within two networks: the DMN and the ECN. DMN regions included the angular gyrus (TPJ), PCC, precuneus cortex, and middle frontal gyrus (mPFC). ECN regions included the frontal pole (dlPFC) and the ACC. These regions were selected based on their known involvement in depression cognitive control processes (Bezmaternykh et al., 2021). Then, to reduce the number of comparisons for the t-test, I reduced the number of ROIs to three: the precuneus and PCC from the DMN, and dlPFC from the ECN.

dmn_regions = ['Angular Gyrus', 'Cingulate Gyrus, posterior division', 'Precuneous Cortex'] #according to the labels
ecn_regions = ['Frontal Pole', 'Middle Frontal Gyrus', 'Cingulate Gyrus, anterior division']
#function to match region names
def find_region_index(region_name, labels):
    for i, label in enumerate(labels):
        if region_name.lower() in label.lower():
            return i
    return None
#indices for regions
dmn_indices = [find_region_index(region, ho_labels) for region in dmn_regions]
ecn_indices = [find_region_index(region, ho_labels) for region in ecn_regions]
#if regions aren't found, they need to be filtered to prevent errors
dmn_indices = [idx for idx in dmn_indices if idx is not None]
ecn_indices = [idx for idx in ecn_indices if idx is not None]
#individual masks for each ROI
roi_masks = {}
for idx, region_name in zip(dmn_indices + ecn_indices, dmn_regions + ecn_regions):
    mask_data = (ho_labels_img.get_fdata() == idx).astype(np.int32) #this was done to prevent 64bit errors
    mask_img = new_img_like(ho_labels_img, mask_data)
    roi_masks[region_name] = mask_img
#and now let's make sure we actually loaded the regions!
for region_name, mask_img in roi_masks.items():
    print(f'Unique values in {region_name} mask: {np.unique(mask_img.get_fdata())}')

For each participant, the time series was extracted from the preprocessed BOLD data using Nilearns NiftiLabelsMasker for all the six predefined ROIs. This included temporal filtering (0.01-0.1 Hz), confound regression, and standardization. Then, I computed functional connectivity using Pearsons correlation between the time series of all six ROIs, creating 6x6 connectivity matrices for each participant. For the within-group analysis, I focused on sex differences within each group. Figure 2 illustrates the connectivity matrices for the depressed and control groups, while figure 3 illustrates the connectivity matrices of females and males within each group.

Statistical Analysis

A t-test was used to compare between the groups for each pair of ROIs. Multiple comparisons were corrected using the False Discovery Rate (FDR), a method that is less stringent than Bonferronis. Effect sizes (Cohens d) were calculated to assess the magnitude of group and sex differences.

In[15]:
control_connectivity = np.array(control_connectivity) #converting to arrays
depressed_connectivity = np.array(depressed_connectivity)
#initializing matrices to store the t-statistics, p-values, and effect sizes (Cohen's d)
t_stat_matrix = np.zeros((6, 6))
p_value_matrix = np.zeros((6, 6))
cohens_d_matrix = np.zeros((6, 6))
#performing t-test for each region and calculating effect sizes
for i in range(6):
    for j in range(6):
        control_values = control_connectivity[:, i, j]
        depressed_values = depressed_connectivity[:, i, j]
        #calculating variances to exclude small variances that might cause any problems
        control_var = np.var(control_values)
        depressed_var = np.var(depressed_values)
        #performing the t-test on big variances
        if control_var > 1e-6 and depressed_var > 1e-6:
            t_stat, p_value = ttest_ind(control_values, depressed_values)
            #calculating effect sizes
            control_mean = np.mean(control_values)
            depressed_mean = np.mean(depressed_values)
            control_std = np.std(control_values, ddof=1)  #SD of control group
            depressed_std = np.std(depressed_values, ddof=1)  #SD of depressed group
            n_control = len(control_values)
            n_depressed = len(depressed_values)
            #pooled SD
            pooled_std = np.sqrt(((n_control - 1) * control_std**2 + (n_depressed - 1) * depressed_std**2) / (n_control + n_depressed - 2))
            #cohen's d
            cohens_d = (control_mean - depressed_mean) / pooled_std if pooled_std > 0 else np.nan
        else:
            t_stat, p_value, cohens_d = np.nan, np.nan, np.nan  #setting to NAN if the variances are too low
        #storing the t-stats, p-values, and effect sizes
        t_stat_matrix[i, j] = t_stat
        p_value_matrix[i, j] = p_value
        cohens_d_matrix[i, j] = cohens_d
#now let's display the significant results
significant_pairs = np.where(p_value_matrix < 0.05)
print("Significant differences found between the following region pairs (with Cohen's d):")
for i, j in zip(significant_pairs[0], significant_pairs[1]):
    print(f"Region {i} vs Region {j}: t-statistic = {t_stat_matrix[i, j]}, p-value = {p_value_matrix[i, j]}, Cohen's d = {cohens_d_matrix[i, j]}")

#let's def a function to calculate cohen's d
def cohen_d(group1, group2):
    n1, n2 = len(group1), len(group2)
    pooled_std = np.sqrt(((n1 - 1) * np.var(group1, ddof=1) + (n2 - 1) * np.var(group2, ddof=1)) / (n1 + n2 - 2))
    return (np.mean(group1) - np.mean(group2)) / pooled_std
#now let's perform t-tests and calculate Cohen's d for each comparison
#Within-DMN connectivity
t_stat_dmn, p_value_dmn = ttest_ind(control_dmn, depressed_dmn)
cohen_d_dmn = cohen_d(control_dmn, depressed_dmn)
#DMN-ECN connectivity
t_stat_dmn_ecn, p_value_dmn_ecn = ttest_ind(control_dmn_ecn, depressed_dmn_ecn)
cohen_d_dmn_ecn = cohen_d(control_dmn_ecn, depressed_dmn_ecn)
#DMN-left fronto-parietal connectivity
t_stat_dmn_fp, p_value_dmn_fp = ttest_ind(control_dmn_fp, depressed_dmn_fp)
cohen_d_dmn_fp = cohen_d(control_dmn_fp, depressed_dmn_fp)
print(f"Within-DMN connectivity: t-statistic = {t_stat_dmn}, p-value = {p_value_dmn}, Cohen's d = {cohen_d_dmn}")
print(f"DMN-ECN connectivity: t-statistic = {t_stat_dmn_ecn}, p-value = {p_value_dmn_ecn}, Cohen's d = {cohen_d_dmn_ecn}")
print(f"DMN-left fronto-parietal connectivity: t-statistic = {t_stat_dmn_fp}, p-value = {p_value_dmn_fp}, Cohen's d = {cohen_d_dmn_fp}")

variance_threshold = 1e-6
for i in range(6):
    for j in range(6):
        control_male_values = control_male_connectivity[:, i, j]
        control_female_values = control_female_connectivity[:, i, j]
        control_male_var = np.var(control_male_values)
        control_female_var = np.var(control_female_values)
        if control_male_var > variance_threshold and control_female_var > variance_threshold:
            t_stat_control, p_value_control = ttest_ind(control_male_values, control_female_values)
            cohens_d_control = cohen_d(control_male_values, control_female_values)
        else:
            t_stat_control, p_value_control, cohens_d_control = np.nan, np.nan, np.nan
        t_stat_matrix_control[i, j] = t_stat_control
        p_value_matrix_control[i, j] = p_value_control
        cohens_d_matrix_control[i, j] = cohens_d_control
for i in range(6):
    for j in range(6):
        depressed_male_values = depressed_male_connectivity[:, i, j]
        depressed_female_values = depressed_female_connectivity[:, i, j]
        depressed_male_var = np.var(depressed_male_values)
        depressed_female_var = np.var(depressed_female_values)
        
        if depressed_male_var > variance_threshold and depressed_female_var > variance_threshold:
            t_stat_depressed, p_value_depressed = ttest_ind(depressed_male_values, depressed_female_values)

        p_value_matrix_depressed[i, j] = p_value_depressed
        cohens_d_matrix_depressed[i, j] = cohens_d_depressed

Results

Between-Group Analysis (Control vs. Depressed)

Before correcting for multiple comparisons, several significant differences were found between groups. There was a significant difference between the precuneus and the frontal pole (t(64) = -2.76, p = .008, Cohens d = -0.73), a significant difference between the PCC and the dlPFC (t(64) = -2.11, p = .039, Cohens d = -0.56), a significant difference between the PCC and the frontal pole (t(64) = -2.2, p = .032, Cohens d = -0.58), a significant difference between the angular gyrus and the dlPFC (t(64) = -2.18, p = .033, Cohens d = -0.58), and a significant difference between the angular gyrus and the frontal pole (t(64) = -2.40, p = .019, Cohens d = -.63). However, after applying the FDR correction, these were all insignificant.

Within-Group Analysis (Males vs. Females)

Within the control group, a significant difference was found between the dlPFC and the ACC (t(19) = 3.36, p = .003, Cohens d = 1.62), and a significant difference was found between the frontal pole and ACC (t(19) = 2.35, p = .029, Cohens d = 1.14). None of these regions were significant after the FDR correction. Within the depressed group, a significant difference was found between the precuneus and the ACC (t(43)= -2.39, p = .005, Cohens d= -0.96), a significant difference between the dlPFC and the frontal pole (t(43) = 2.16, p = .036, Cohens d = 0.71), and a significant difference between the dlPFC and the ACC (t(43) = -2.33, p = .024, Cohens d = -.77). These findings werent significant after the FDR correction.

Discussion

The current research aimed to explore differences in resting-state functional connectivity between healthy controls and patients with MDD, focusing on sex differences within each group. Although there were significant findings, none remained after applying the FDR correction. However, the effect sizes observed in this study suggest that certain connectivity differences shouldnt be overlooked, even in an absence of a significant p-value.
The DMN regions (precuneus, PCC, and angular gyrus) showed differences in connectivity with the ECN regions (dlPFC and frontal pole). The effect sizes for these regions ranged from medium to large. The findings indicate that there is a reduced connectivity between the DMN and ECN regions in depressed patients compared to controls. The negative Cohens d suggest that the connectivity was lower in the depressed group. These findings align with previous research on altered DMN-ECN connectivity in depression (Bezmaternykh et al., 2021). In the control group, there were sex differences in the dlPFC and ACC, and the frontal pole and ACC, where males showed higher connectivity than females. In the depressed group, females had stronger connectivity between the precuneus and the ACC, suggesting that females with depression may experience more connectivity between the DMN and the ACC. This could mean that females tend to ruminate more, according to previous findings (Bezmaternykh et al., 2021). Depressed males had stronger connectivity between the dlPFC and the frontal pole, crucial regions for cognitive control (Bezmaternykh et al., 2021). Females had stronger connectivity between the dlPFC and ACC, suggesting an integration of cognitive control regions and emotional regulation regions.
While these results suggest that females tend to ruminate more while males rely on cognitive control networks, these results are hesitant since no p-value remained significant after the FDR correction. The small sample size might have contributed to this. Small samples, in addition to reducing statistical power, tend to also inflate effect sizes. There also could be outliers present in the data, contributing to high effect sizes, or even low within-group variance.
Future research should replicate these findings with larger and more balanced samples to estimate effect sizes better, or focus on more ROIs to capture more patterns of connectivity.
